<paragraph id="F21BB0F44D05B46900DDF553E6D0197D" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3BA36D69B588A7992FA58C88108A3D7E" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">
Known only on Hiva Oa, Marquesas Islands, from a single population in the vicinity of Mt. Temetiu, on the 
<normalizedToken id="45E5EC7344E4FB7C4CCB0285F098B6E5" originalValue="island’s">island's</normalizedToken>
central summit crest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C09CA252F34142277EB730B2E42C57D6" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="31362F855666F321899D13847F3C3A42" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B8C2D53272A92C0BCC2A43DC1AE2D124" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName id="4F6AA7F348362585AA98174AA7F07B4A" authorityName="Lorence &amp; K. R. Wood" authorityYear="2011" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="marquesensis">
<emphasis id="DF450EC3B9B62A975DA3B89236EC66E6" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris marquesensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs at 1000-1200 m elevation in low, windswept, montane wet forests and shrublands with 
<taxonomicName id="1BF1E50AEA08535FF8394650BEC00B98" authorityName="Brack" authorityYear="1854" class="Hexapoda" family="Geometridae" genus="Alsophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tahitensis">
<emphasis id="4B101020EE0E9D607A5937B3D5BD82E8" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Alsophila tahitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="12909BDD9E8E4D29C9B4D04C7FE2D9B0" authorityName="Frodin" authorityYear="1990" baseAuthorityName="Decne." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Cheirodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Apiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bastardianum">
<emphasis id="7CD6973C3E7AD8B7B886302C61902E25" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Cheirodendron bastardianum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="3DE3E19DB7A9302A9FE6FC2442A5868C" authorityName="J. R. Forster &amp; G. Forster" authorityYear="1775" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rhizophoraceae" genus="Crossostylis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="biflora">
<emphasis id="94F4974B314EDAE451D344F57F107560" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Crossostylis biflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5EEC84249EF5BFDE38470A992E6A5A0C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Cyrtandra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D1594DCFA8309E965FC502D139A2270A" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Cyrtandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<taxonomicName id="D1277108D373C9D38FEC6F531BD75E73" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Freycinetia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Pandanales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B519E2C27C5E63C577DE683219218AA8" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Freycinetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.
<emphasis id="6694A490EC2F2A84C4997235591EF569" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">, Leptochloa marquisensis</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DFB345E2D579920EE61DA5A65AD59EE3" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rutaceae" genus="Melicope" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Rutales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9CE7619B92FCB1B7884469F2C5B3A117" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Melicope</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<taxonomicName id="F894BEC83E024CD1CB79F6023A622DBF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Metrosideros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="collina">
<emphasis id="9EA5AE21C6F8C8F71FCB658E56536AD7" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Metrosideros collina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6B00F7FB7E4AEAE58AB3C11D6F41D80F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Psychotria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Gentianales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C0DC27AE8AF7E5D592D2E6C23ADF26BB" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Psychotria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.
<emphasis id="D6E1C28D84AD9E6B1369567CCAE9A9B1" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">, Weinmannia marquesana</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="48F9E76D088073C2E0367937E3909BA4" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">marquesana</emphasis>
, and abundant pteridophytes in the understory. This new species is rare and localized, although in one area it occurs in dense colonies of hundreds of plants that completely cover wet banks and rock faces in and around shallow depressions or grottos, with fronds often appressed to the rock face (K. Wood, pers. obs.). Threats to this species include rooting by feral pigs and invasion by aggressive alien plant species, notably 
<taxonomicName id="9DC9B7C804C0BD4F77E425CEB66FAACB" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Asteraceae" genus="Elephantopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Campanulales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis id="62A3C4DD6132DF5906EBEB9C2DDCD0E7" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Elephantopus mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EAD435A1C453B57CF36E16A05079AF26" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Psidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guajava">
<emphasis id="2742F5FBBC658AAC73C1344413749E63" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Psidium guajava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="8CA613665B0246DD2D6F3414329E82C5" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Syzygium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtiflorae" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="cumini">
<emphasis id="C8C2BE44D403F14AAA90C0AAB030E347" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Syzygium cumini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4B0A7DE454D72F00F6D500990ACAB0EA" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="D3C3A984481FA9122CF9433A7361F19A" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EC562036C808D1E08CD1ADFEF3E0B3AD" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">This new species is named for the Marquesas Islands, where it is known currently known only from Hiva Oa.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9EB958A6A8A413FFABC1CFDAB5496DE" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="1C3C35FB5EA31DF58BDC0323C1A0BAC0" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="189AA6764FEF310FDE06D9B6FC9B07B7" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">
Proposed IUCN Red List Category 
<emphasis id="F7DB965D865F298411EAE23A8F001FB4" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Critically Endangered</emphasis>
(CR): B2a, B2b 
<normalizedToken id="523FB0FBCAE6F5B8990D862482F0D38E" originalValue="i–iii">i-iii</normalizedToken>
): B1, extent of occurrence estimated to be less than 100 km2; B2, area of occupancy estimated to be less than 10 km2 (ca. 9 km2), and B2a, a single population known; b (
<normalizedToken id="FDAA18D82EB90DFE6819B2804EBAE9A3" originalValue="i–iii">i-iii</normalizedToken>
), habitat continuing decline inferred. The suitable habitat for 
<taxonomicName id="1209290E9489BDAC8B46A77D1602D6D9" authorityName="Lorence &amp; K. R. Wood" authorityYear="2011" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="marquesensis">
<emphasis id="77BA457A53CDF7E6088085B9CE8953D6" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris marquesensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on Hiva Oa (ca. 315 km2), confined to Mt. Temetiu and vicinity, is indicated as an endangered environment, threatened by human activity (deforestation and fire), feral animals (pigs), and invasive plants, reducing the extent of the forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AB709BE4E24A223BC5F6F4A9AF3A9DC8" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F0D3474C085688306A6AC06EFFEA837F" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="64B2B0186A02272B13304D4B9C6A0317" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">
This new species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4E6BE3223803E094FCE5D910F1020175" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1941" baseAuthorityName="E. D. Br." class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="quaylei">
<emphasis id="0C326D63AF0181C4330E7A62577FA380" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris quaylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its much smaller habit (although some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="B6BFEF06A50338A8C69B958D4EFEFAFB" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1941" baseAuthorityName="E. D. Br." class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="quaylei">
<emphasis id="90D867099A24EBC6DBBFADB07E70CCDE" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris quaylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Ua Huka summit are atypically small), fronds with 1-3, gradually reduced basal pairs of pinnae, and lack of sessile glands on the lamina surfaces (but present on indusial margins), a feature it shares with 
<taxonomicName id="BF5D81119278F1FE5BD676FEA8962E20" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1941" baseAuthorityName="Fourn." class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="fasciculata">
<emphasis id="908B4333A3ADAAE975087CFD078AC2D7" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris fasciculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ching from New Caledonia, New Guinea, and the Celebes (
<bibRefCitation id="428DDA6172DAD07F951CAD2758B1E805" author="Holttum, RE" journalOrPublisher="Allertonia" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" pagination="169 - 234" refId="B22" refString="Holttum, RE, 1977. The family Thelypteridaceae in the Pacific and Australasia. Allertonia 1: 169 - 234" title="The family Thelypteridaceae in the Pacific and Australasia." volume="1" year="1977">Holttum 1977</bibRefCitation>
). Although 
<taxonomicName id="E7E6923D5E2A48D05C16DC21936C57F7" authorityName="Lorence &amp; K. R. Wood" authorityYear="2011" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="marquesensis">
<emphasis id="8BDF14AB73EA854CE7AB01643D3AA1F6" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris marquesensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may occur in the vicinity of 
<taxonomicName id="1B20DAA095CA2131604C69E25C888EEB" authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1941" baseAuthorityName="E. D. Br." class="Polypodiopsida" family="Thelypteridaceae" genus="Thelypteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polypodiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="27" phylum="Polypodiopsida" rank="species" species="quaylei">
<emphasis id="811BCCB645DDC451CBDE8F8FB5D79386" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="27">Thelypteris quaylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lorence et al. 8942, PTBG), the latter species tends to grow in wet forest understory either terres 
<pageBreakToken id="91F23BF4F4B248D1A96F7573209E8FE8" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" start="start">trially</pageBreakToken>
or on mossy boulders, although it is sometimes found in shady depressions on steep ridge slopes either as individuals or forming small colonies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
